<paragraph blockId="10.[151,518,151,177]" box="[151,518,151,177]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,518,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,518,151,177]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Wanat, 2001" authorityName="Wanat" authorityYear="2001" box="[238,518,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[238,352,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Tetrapion</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wanat" box="[361,518,151,177]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" refString="Wanat, M. (2001) Genera of Australo-Pacific Rhadinocybinae and Myrmacicelinae, with biogeography of the Apionidae (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea) and phylogeny of the Brentidae (s. lato). Mantis, Olsztyn, 432 pp." type="book" year="2001">
Wanat, 
<number box="[459,518,151,177]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,222,1182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
This is another very diverse genus, comprising probably not less than 
<number box="[941,969,222,246]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="24.0">24</number>
species in Grande Terre. Several of them (all undescribed) were collected from various species of 
<taxonomicName box="[815,883,259,283]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[815,883,259,283]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Codia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[902,1054,258,282]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cunoniaceae</taxonomicName>
). Adults of one species (over 
<specimenCount pageId="10" pageNumber="69" type="generic">
<number box="[1408,1436,258,282]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="40.0">40</number>
specimens
</specimenCount>
collected) were observed feeding on young leaves of 
<taxonomicName box="[876,1044,294,318]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis box="[876,1044,294,318]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Codia discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
several times (
<figureCitation box="[1214,1352,294,318]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 20. 15" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1845,1868]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,287,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,287,1832]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 20. 15) Pterapion kanalae feeding on fresh leaf of Pycnandra balansae; 16) Aprotapion hamiota feeding on Codia incrassata; 16) feeding holes of Tetrapion n. sbgen. et sp. on C. incrassata; 17) adult of Tetrapion n. sbgen. et sp. feeding on inflorescence of C. incrassata; 18, 19) feeding holes of Tetrapion (s. str.) sp. on fresh stems and leaves of C. discolor. (phot.: all—MW; sites: 15 — Aoupinié, 16 — ca. 1 km NW Mt Mandjélia, 17, 18 — Mt Mandjélia, 19, 20 — Bois du Sud)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282870/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Figs. 19, 20</figureCitation>
). Other plants associated with the weevils are 
<taxonomicName box="[589,704,331,355]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jaffreyi">
<emphasis box="[589,608,331,354]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[624,704,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">jaffreyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[719,819,331,355]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis box="[719,738,331,354]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[754,819,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">nitida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and (in the North of Grande Terre) 
<taxonomicName box="[1241,1392,331,355]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incrassata">
<emphasis box="[1241,1260,331,354]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1276,1392,332,355]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">incrassata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, on which at least two members of 
<taxonomicName box="[502,610,367,390]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[502,610,367,390]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Tetrapion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[618,677,367,390]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
have regularly been observed, apart from another, wingless species representing a new subgenus (see below). Seven specimens of one species were collected at night from one plant of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,402,438,462]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Pancheria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="billardierii">
<emphasis box="[151,402,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Pancheria billardierii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, another 
<taxonomicName box="[517,662,438,462]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cunoniaceae</taxonomicName>
[
<number box="[682,716,438,462]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="22.0">22</number>
]. In some northern and central localities (Thoven, Aoupinié, Mandjélia, Farino) 
<number box="[375,417,474,498]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
undescribed species of 
<taxonomicName box="[700,808,476,499]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[700,808,476,499]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Tetrapion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of one distinct species-group were repeatedly beaten, often in numbers, from 
<taxonomicName box="[416,631,510,534]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Guioa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="microsepala">
<emphasis box="[416,631,510,534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Guioa microsepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[644,742,510,534]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Guioa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis box="[644,661,511,534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[675,742,510,534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[756,863,510,534]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Guioa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis box="[756,773,511,534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[787,863,510,534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[924,1064,511,534]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Cupaniopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[924,1064,511,534]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Cupaniopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (all 
<taxonomicName box="[1204,1349,510,534]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Sapindaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,222,1182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Most members of 
<taxonomicName box="[419,527,548,571]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[419,527,548,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Tetrapion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have short, thick, and sexually not differentiated rostra, allowing for a very shallow deposition of eggs, presumably subcortical or directly into soft, green tissues. Such a shape for the female rostrum generally excludes larval development in reproductive organs of the plant, and indeed, the beetles have never been observed on flowers or fruits. However, several poorly known, tiny species of this diverse genus have females with long, thin and curved rostra specialized for preparation of deeper oviposition holes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,222,1182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Although recently collected several times in Grande Terre and Loyalty Is (Lifou), nothing can be concluded about plant preferences of 
<taxonomicName authority="Wanat, 2001" authorityName="Wanat" authorityYear="2001" box="[467,839,762,787]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracicum" subGenus="Axinapion">
<emphasis box="[467,480,764,787]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">T</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[508,525,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">A</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[553,681,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">thoracicum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wanat" box="[692,839,762,786]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" refString="Wanat, M. (2001) Genera of Australo-Pacific Rhadinocybinae and Myrmacicelinae, with biogeography of the Apionidae (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea) and phylogeny of the Brentidae (s. lato). Mantis, Olsztyn, 432 pp." type="book" year="2001">
Wanat, 
<number box="[780,839,762,786]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the sole member of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[1256,1379,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Axinapion.</emphasis>
One specimen was incidentally beaten from 
<taxonomicName box="[595,825,798,822]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapotaceae" genus="Pycnandra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="balansae">
<emphasis box="[595,825,798,822]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Pycnandra balansae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[840,969,798,822]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapotaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Sapotaceae</taxonomicName>
) in Aoupinié [
<number box="[1132,1166,798,822]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="23.0">23</number>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,222,1182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
A peculiar flightless species was discovered on Mt Mandjélia by Mrs L. E. Cheesmann nearly 
<number box="[1263,1291,834,858]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="60.0">60</number>
years ago (
<number box="[1424,1436,834,858]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="1.0">1</number>
<number box="[151,172,871,895]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="3.0">3</number>
, Natural History Museum, London), and provisionally placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Apterapion" authorityName="Apterapion" box="[903,1167,870,894]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Pterapion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[903,1015,871,894]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Pterapion</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1032,1158,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Apterapion</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wanat" box="[1210,1366,870,894]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" refString="Wanat, M. (2001) Genera of Australo-Pacific Rhadinocybinae and Myrmacicelinae, with biogeography of the Apionidae (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea) and phylogeny of the Brentidae (s. lato). Mantis, Olsztyn, 432 pp." type="book" year="2001">
Wanat (
<number box="[1296,1357,870,894]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. After a re-discovery of this species on the summit of Mt Mandjélia by MW in 
<number box="[962,1021,906,930]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2007.0">2007</number>
, and thorough morphological studies of several dozen specimens of both sexes, the species is now considered to represent a new subgenus within 
<taxonomicName box="[151,257,980,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,257,980,1003]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Tetrapion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, not a congener of 
<emphasis box="[478,704,979,1003]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Apterapion 
<taxonomicName box="[612,704,979,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Aprotapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamiota">hamiota</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. It is noteworthy that both these species were found on the same host and plant community, but allopatric on two hills separated by less than 
<quantity box="[1092,1160,1014,1038]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" unit="km" value="1.0">1 km</quantity>
. The new 
<taxonomicName box="[1295,1400,1015,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Coleoptera" genus="Tetrapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1400,1015,1038]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Tetrapion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is monophagous on 
<taxonomicName box="[358,554,1051,1075]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incrassata">
<emphasis box="[358,554,1051,1075]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">Codia incrassata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[572,723,1050,1074]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cunoniaceae</taxonomicName>
), and beetles feed both on inflorescences (
<figureCitation box="[1224,1309,1050,1074]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 20. 15" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1845,1868]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,287,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,287,1832]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 20. 15) Pterapion kanalae feeding on fresh leaf of Pycnandra balansae; 16) Aprotapion hamiota feeding on Codia incrassata; 16) feeding holes of Tetrapion n. sbgen. et sp. on C. incrassata; 17) adult of Tetrapion n. sbgen. et sp. feeding on inflorescence of C. incrassata; 18, 19) feeding holes of Tetrapion (s. str.) sp. on fresh stems and leaves of C. discolor. (phot.: all—MW; sites: 15 — Aoupinié, 16 — ca. 1 km NW Mt Mandjélia, 17, 18 — Mt Mandjélia, 19, 20 — Bois du Sud)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282870/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Fig. 
<number box="[1280,1309,1050,1074]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
) and fresh leaves (
<figureCitation box="[235,318,1086,1110]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 20. 15" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1845,1868]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,287,1826]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,287,1832]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 20. 15) Pterapion kanalae feeding on fresh leaf of Pycnandra balansae; 16) Aprotapion hamiota feeding on Codia incrassata; 16) feeding holes of Tetrapion n. sbgen. et sp. on C. incrassata; 17) adult of Tetrapion n. sbgen. et sp. feeding on inflorescence of C. incrassata; 18, 19) feeding holes of Tetrapion (s. str.) sp. on fresh stems and leaves of C. discolor. (phot.: all—MW; sites: 15 — Aoupinié, 16 — ca. 1 km NW Mt Mandjélia, 17, 18 — Mt Mandjélia, 19, 20 — Bois du Sud)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282870/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">
Fig. 
<number box="[287,318,1086,1110]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
). Nevertheless, no hypothesis can be formulated about the way of larval development of this species after negative results from 
<emphasis box="[452,521,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">in situ</emphasis>
controls of flower heads and fresh leaf buds of 
<taxonomicName box="[1054,1203,1123,1147]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Codia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incrassata">
<emphasis box="[1054,1073,1123,1146]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1086,1203,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="69">incrassata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<date box="[1238,1388,1122,1147]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2007-01">
January 
<number box="[1332,1388,1122,1146]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</date>
and 
<date box="[151,336,1158,1182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2008-11">
November 
<number box="[276,336,1158,1182]" pageId="10" pageNumber="69" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</date>
.
</paragraph>
